05204nam a22005895i 9780520938717DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209387177 a10.1525/97805209387172doi  a(DE-B1597)519190  a(OCoLC)60312438  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHV91b.R4225 2005eb 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a362.5/568/09732221 aReese, Ellen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBacklash against Welfare Mothers :bPast and Present /cEllen Reese. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (372 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Deferred Dreams, Broken Families, And Hardship: The Impact Of Welfare Reform -- t2. Attacking Welfare, Promoting Work And Marriage: Continuity And Change In Welfare Opposition -- t3. The 1950S Welfare Backlash And Federal Complicity -- t4. Explaining The Postwar Rise Of Welfare Opposition -- t5. Southern Welfare Backlashes: Georgia And Kentucky -- t6. Western And Northern Welfare Backlashes: California And New York -- t7. Setting The Stage: The Failures Of Liberal Innovation -- t8. The Rise Of The Republican Right And The New Democrats -- t9. Business Interests, Conservative Think Tanks, And The Assault On Welfare -- t10. Congressional Attacks On Welfare, 1980-2004 -- t11. Rebuilding The Welfare State: Forging A New Deal For Working Families -- tAppendix 1: States That Restricted Eligibility For ADC (1949-1960) -- tAppendix 2: Variables And Data Sources Used In Quantitative Analysis -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBacklash against Welfare Mothers is a forceful examination of how and why a state-level revolt against welfare, begun in the late 1940s, was transformed into a national-level assault that destroyed a critical part of the nation's safety net, with tragic consequences for American society. With a wealth of original research, Ellen Reese puts recent debates about the contemporary welfare backlash into historical perspective. She provides a closer look at these early antiwelfare campaigns, showing why they were more successful in some states than others and how opponents of welfare sometimes targeted Puerto Ricans and Chicanos as well as blacks for cutbacks. Her research reveals both the continuities and changes in American welfare opposition from the late 1940s to the present. Reese brings new evidence to light that reveals how large farmers and racist politicians, concerned about the supply of cheap labor, appealed to white voters' racial resentments and stereotypes about unwed mothers, blacks, and immigrants in the 1950s. She then examines congressional failure to replace the current welfare system with a more popular alternative in the 1960s and 1970s, which paved the way for national assaults on welfare. Taking a fresh look at recent debates on welfare reform, she explores how and why politicians competing for the white vote and right-wing think tanks promoting business interests appeased the Christian right and manufactured consent for cutbacks through a powerful, racially coded discourse. Finally, through firsthand testimonies, Reese vividly portrays the tragic consequences of current welfare policies and calls for a bold new agenda for working families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAid to families with dependent children programs. 0aPublic welfarexHistoryxUnited States. 0aPublic welfarezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSingle mothersxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aSingle mothersxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aWelfare recipie